Case law suggests that whether an agreement will be deemed to be unenforceable as being an unreasonable restraint of trade will turn on its facts, including the terms of the agreement (for example, the size of the consideration, the duration of the agreement, and the relative obligations of the parties); whether the agreement is in standard form or has been the subject of negotiation; and the experience and age of the person arguing that the contract is in restraint of trade.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A key case in terms of setting out the principles regarding how the doctrine of restraint of trade applies in the field of entertainment contracts is 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://uk.practicallaw.thomsonreuters.com/D-016-1571?originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=PLUK1.0&transitionType=PLDocumentLink&contextData=(sc.Default)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Schroeder Music Publishing Co v Macaulay [1974] 1 WLR 1308
}\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 }}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, in which the House of Lords considered whether a publishing agreement entered into between a young, unknown songwriter and a music publisher was in restraint of trade. It approached the question by asking:
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 \sa0 \sb0 {\fi-360 \li {\*\pn \pnlvlblt \ilvl0 \ls19 \pnindent0 \pnf1 {\f2 \pntxtb \u8226\'3f}}{\listtext \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \u8226\'3f\tab }\ls19 {\pntext }
{\pard }\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa180 \sb0 
Were the terms of the agreement so restrictive that either they could not be justified at all, or they had to be justified by the party seeking to enforce the agreement?
\par {\pntext }
}
}
}
}
}\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \sa180 \sb0 {\fi-360 \li {\*\pn \pnlvlblt \ilvl0 \ls20 \pnindent0 \pnf1 {\f2 \pntxtb \u8226\'3f}}{\listtext \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \u8226\'3f\tab }\ls20 {\pntext }
{\pard }\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa180 \sb0 
If there was room for justification, had that party proved justification (normally by showing that the restrictions were no more than what was reasonably required to protect their legitimate interests)?
\par {\pntext }
}
}
}
}
}\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \sa180 \sb0 \intbl 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri100 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li100 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
The agreement was for a five-year period, extending to ten years if the royalties for the first five years exceeded \u163\'3f5,000 (an amount the court commented was a modest sum). Under the agreement, the composer assigned to the publisher for all time copyright in all the work he composed, during the period, receiving no payment (apart from an initial \u163\'3f50) unless the work was published by the publisher. The House of Lords commented that there was no evidence as to why such a long period was necessary. Other factors it highlighted were that the agreement was in a standard form, the publisher was under no obligation to use the composer\rquote s material, the composer also had no right to terminate the agreement (the existence of which might have given the agreement a different appearance), and the composer had no right to have his copyrights reassigned to him.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
It concluded that the agreement was an unreasonable restraint of trade because it tied the composer for a period of years so that the composer\rquote s work would be sterilised and he could earn nothing from his abilities as a composer if the publisher chose not to publish the work.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Other examples of cases which provide further illustrations of how the doctrine of restraint of trade has been applied in the entertainment context include:
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 \sa0 \sb0 {\fi-360 \li {\*\pn \pnlvlblt \ilvl0 \ls21 \pnindent0 \pnf1 {\f2 \pntxtb \u8226\'3f}}{\listtext \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \u8226\'3f\tab }\ls21 {\pntext }
{\pard }\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://uk.practicallaw.thomsonreuters.com/D-016-1572?originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=PLUK1.0&transitionType=PLDocumentLink&contextData=(sc.Default)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Silvertone Records Ltd v Mountfield and others [1993] EMLR 152
}\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 }}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa180 \sb0 
, in which the High Court held that an exclusive worldwide recording agreement entered into by the Stone Roses for (up to) a seven-year period was unenforceable as being in restraint of trade. The court held that the agreement was an unreasonable restraint of trade because, among other things, of the one-sided nature of the terms, which put the minimum commitment and release entirely within the record company\rquote s control, so that the band could be sterilised for seven years; and the immense inequality in bargaining power and negotiating ability between the parties \u8211\'3f in particular, the band had no legal or business experience, little income, and were represented by a lawyer with no experience in the music industry.
\par {\pntext }
}
}
}
}
}\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \sa180 \sb0 {\fi-360 \li {\*\pn \pnlvlblt \ilvl0 \ls22 \pnindent0 \pnf1 {\f2 \pntxtb \u8226\'3f}}{\listtext \b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 \u8226\'3f\tab }\ls22 {\pntext }
{\pard }\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li480 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://uk.practicallaw.thomsonreuters.com/D-009-1862?originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=PLUK1.0&transitionType=PLDocumentLink&contextData=(sc.Default)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Wadlow v Samuel [2007] EWCA Civ 155
}\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 }}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, in which the High Court rejected the artist Seal\rquote s argument that an agreement under which his manager was entitled to post-term commission on monies arising, recordings made, compositions written and residual fees arising from performances given or negotiated during the period of the agreement, was unenforceable as being in restraint of trade. The court held that it was counter-intuitive to describe an obligation to pay money as a restraint of trade, even where it continued after the end of the management agreement. The judge distinguished 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Armatrading v Stone (unreported), 17 September 1984
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, in which such a term had been held to be in restraint of trade, because it considered that the manager\rquote s contract in that case was materially different, with a wide-ranging entitlement to post-term commission which could potentially cover virtually all the artist\rquote s earnings for many years after the termination and might well make it very difficult for the artist to engage a new manager (since the artist might be unable to afford to pay commission to two managers on the same income stream). Further, the judge said that the term in issue in 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Wadlow v Samuel
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, while unusual, was not unreasonable. (Such a term may, however, be deemed disadvantageous so as to give rise to a presumption of undue influence (see 
}
