{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The definition of \ldblquote Minimum Commitment\rdblquote  sets the parameters for what is expected, at a minimum, of the artists in a given contract period (as defined in the agreement). In the definition, the minimum commitment is defined as, in each contract period, no less than 12 studio recordings of previously unreleased musical works.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Traditional definitions of the minimum commitment were for one album, which would be defined by reference to playing time and number of tracks. However, in the digital era, the album as a collected body of works is having less and less a coherent meaning, in particular in relation to the initial contract period, since single tracks may be released to test the market, so that the idea of an album having to be delivered together has less relevance. The agreement defines the minimum commitment by reference to studio recordings. It is generally accepted that live recordings do not fulfil the minimum commitment. The format in which recordings are delivered may be specified in this definition or in 
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_anchor_a508655_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Clause 3.5
}\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 }}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, or, alternatively, it can be left open if the desired format is not known at the time of contracting.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
