{\b0 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
The minimum commitment is not defined as being satisfied by the recording of any 12 tracks, but by 12 tracks that are mutually agreed between the parties (as being intended to be released as singles or as part of an album). Prior to the delivery of the minimum commitment, numerous demos may have been produced in order to select the album tracks. In some agreements the selection process may be weighted more in favour of the company or the artists. This depends entirely on the nature of the act (for example, a manufactured pop band will typically have no say in the selection of recordings, whereas a guitar band with a significant following and years of performing together may have more say in the matter). However, since the company is financing the production, the company should never fully cede its right to decide which tracks are recorded.
